communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus (CCHFV) is considered to be one of the major emerging disease threats spreading to and within the European Union following an expanding distribution of its main vector, ticks of the genus _Hyalomma_. The first detection of CCHF cases in Turkey was in 2002; since then, more than 9700 cases have been reported, with an overall mortality rate just under 5%. - Mod.UBA]

******
[2] Covid-19 & CCHF coinfection
Date: 3 Jun 2021
Source: Daily Sabah [edited]
https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/woman-becomes-turkeys-first-cchf-covid-19-patient-beats-both/news


A female patient made Turkish medical history as the 1st patient to be infected with both the coronavirus and Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF), a zoonotic virus, at the same time. She also managed to recover. The woman, in her 60s, was recently admitted to the hospital at Karadeniz Technical University (KTU) in the northern province of Trabzon. She had symptoms including high fever, fatigue, and respiratory failure. Experts say though rare, it may become more common as the coronavirus pandemic continues, along with CCHF, which killed 13 people across the country this year [2021].

Professor Selcuk Kaya, head of the infectious diseases department at the university, says they were double-checking patients who had both the coronavirus and the tickborne disease, noting that both show similar symptoms.

"The patient was admitted 10 days ago with a preliminary diagnosis of COVID-19. We were already on alert for CCHF as this is a region where CCHF cases are common, especially in high-altitude areas in the (regional) provinces of Gumushane, Bayburt and Giresun. When she was diagnosed with both, we launched a treatment process, 1st for COVID-19 and then supportive therapy for CCHF. In 10 days, her blood levels and overall health were back to normal, and she did not need intensive care," Kaya said.

Kaya said it was inevitable to come across such a case when both diseases were prevalent in the region but that it was important to diagnose it correctly. "Without extra attention, she would be applied treatment only for COVID-19," he added.

